WEBVTT

00:00.962 --> 00:04.125
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.686 --> 00:18.380
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.121 --> 00:26.649
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.709 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.980
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:40.486 --> 00:41.507
Peace be with you, friends.

00:41.527 --> 00:46.433
For the second Sunday of Advent, we have this magnificent reading from Isaiah chapter 11.

00:46.574 --> 00:51.860
And it's this description of the Messiah's arrival, becoming from the root of Jesse.

00:52.621 --> 00:56.306
And then coming to full expression in the Messiah,

00:56.578 --> 00:58.100
are the gifts of the Holy Spirit.

00:58.561 --> 01:03.529
You know, I was just at Shark Cathedral last summer filming, one of my favorite places in the world.

01:03.569 --> 01:07.576
And on the Western front, there's a depiction of this, just gorgeous.

01:08.036 --> 01:19.695
Shows Jesse asleep, and then coming up from his loins is this great tree, and then these very figures on it, the ancestors of Jesus, at the top of the tree, kind of as its flower, is the figure of Christ.

01:20.115 --> 01:24.242
And around his head are the seven doves symbolic of the seven

01:24.642 --> 01:25.663
gifts of the Holy Spirit.

01:26.024 --> 01:30.188
So that image from medieval France goes all the way back to ancient Israel.

01:30.849 --> 01:36.996
And this passage that's our first reading, on that day, the great day of the Lord, right?

01:37.016 --> 01:40.680
A shoot shall sprout from the stump of Jesse, so from the root of Jesse.

01:41.281 --> 01:43.183
And from his roots, a bud shall blossom.

01:43.704 --> 01:45.806
The spirit of the Lord shall rest upon him.

01:45.866 --> 01:52.434
So Isaiah is anticipating the Messiah, the Mashiach, the anointed one, that will come from the line of David, right?

01:52.962 --> 02:03.477
And you'll have these gifts, namely, a spirit of wisdom and of understanding, a spirit of counsel and of strength, a spirit of knowledge and fear of the Lord.

02:04.698 --> 02:11.187
This is the root of this great tradition which comes up now from the Bible into the fathers and through the great theologians.

02:11.228 --> 02:14.893
Think Gregory the Great, Augustine, Thomas Aquinas, all of them.

02:15.413 --> 02:18.738
Speculate upon these gifts of the Holy Spirit.

02:18.850 --> 02:26.240
And you want to trace it even further, come up to the last confirmation homily I gave, which would have been just a few weeks ago as we recorded these words.

02:26.801 --> 02:41.000
And I talked to the kids about the gifts of the Holy Spirit, because we say at confirmation, when they are confirmed with the presence of the Spirit, I always tell them the Spirit never comes empty-handed, but he comes bearing gifts.

02:41.280 --> 02:48.850
Well, that sermon goes all the way back through the great tradition, all the way to Isaiah chapter 11.

02:49.218 --> 03:02.438
as an advent reading, as we're anticipating again the coming of the Messiah, the one who comes bearing these gifts, the one who calls us, listen now, into his life so that we might share these gifts.

03:03.239 --> 03:06.324
It's good for us to be reflecting on these seven.

03:07.326 --> 03:16.780
So the first gift of Holy Spirit in the great tradition is wisdom, a Sapiencia in Latin, a Sophia in Greek.

03:17.481 --> 03:18.162
What's wisdom?

03:18.786 --> 03:21.088
I've always loved Thomas Aquinas' characterization.

03:21.349 --> 03:24.793
Wisdom is not just, you know, scientific knowledge or insight.

03:25.373 --> 03:33.662
Wisdom is the view from the hilltop, he says, which is to say, from the standpoint of the highest or first cause.

03:34.783 --> 03:41.310
So I can look at my world, you know, with scientific eyes and economic eyes, political eyes, I can take in, you know, what's around me.

03:41.390 --> 03:48.338
But to see the totality of my experience from the standpoint of the highest cause

03:48.738 --> 03:53.945
To see it, use that old phrase, substantiate ternitatis, right, from the aspect of eternity.

03:53.985 --> 04:00.394
To see it as God sees it, that's wisdom.

04:00.935 --> 04:09.127
You know, I often think about this when I take off in an airplane and you're on the ground, you're looking around and the plane takes off and so quickly you get up.

04:09.147 --> 04:14.194
And let's say you're leaving a major city and you can see the whole city.

04:14.626 --> 04:18.070
And you take it in from a whole different perspective.

04:18.130 --> 04:19.993
You see the whole city.

04:20.874 --> 04:22.035
Well, wisdom is like that.

04:22.996 --> 04:25.479
It's seeing your life as God does.

04:26.441 --> 04:29.284
And you know, everybody, this is kind of a rare thing.

04:29.344 --> 04:32.288
It truly is a gift to have that vision.

04:32.688 --> 04:38.195
Because most of us, we kind of schlep our way through life, looking at what's right in front of us.

04:39.357 --> 04:43.762
But to look at the whole of your life from the standpoint of God, that's wisdom.

04:44.770 --> 04:49.858
Okay, next we have, they're usually coupled together, understanding and knowledge.

04:50.839 --> 04:57.630
I often tell the confirmation kids, when you receive these gifts, it doesn't mean like automatically you'll understand all of trigonometry.

04:58.631 --> 05:09.067
They have to do, Aquinas tells us with insight into holy things, insight into the meaning of holy things.

05:09.128 --> 05:10.770
That's understanding and knowledge.

05:11.426 --> 05:15.810
You know, again, most of us go through life and we were knowing all sorts of things.

05:16.171 --> 05:23.258
We're using our minds, our reason to make our way economically or politically or in our relationships or whatever.

05:23.598 --> 05:24.239
I mean, fine.

05:25.100 --> 05:30.485
But how much time do we spend delving into the meaning of really holy things?

05:32.146 --> 05:39.794
The Eucharist, the real presence of Jesus in the Eucharist, the incarnation that God becomes one of us.

05:39.874 --> 05:45.303
The meaning of the cross, that by the blood of his cross, Jesus saves us from our sins.

05:45.343 --> 05:46.505
What does that mean?

05:47.707 --> 05:55.160
The Trinity, the Father sent the Son all the way to God forsaken us so that we might be gathered into the love of the Holy Spirit.

05:55.400 --> 05:57.865
Okay, that's about as deep as it gets.

05:59.507 --> 06:00.609
What do these things mean?

06:02.252 --> 06:03.755
Do we search them out?

06:04.436 --> 06:05.778
Do we spend time

06:06.018 --> 06:09.982
seeking to understand them and then savoring what we understand.

06:10.202 --> 06:22.774
My guess is rarely, and I can see even as I list those, I can see people maybe rolling their eyes like, hey, you know, I got enough to preoccupy me in this life without, you know, worrying about those things.

06:23.454 --> 06:24.395
Yeah, but think about something.

06:26.037 --> 06:28.439
Politics, economics, friendship, relationships.

06:29.060 --> 06:35.666
Yeah, those preoccupy us for the few decades that were here on earth,

06:36.898 --> 06:42.125
But the really holy things will preoccupy us for all eternity.

06:43.146 --> 06:44.208
What's more important?

06:44.989 --> 06:46.591
What's more important to think about?

06:47.592 --> 06:53.480
See, which is why these gifts of understanding and knowledge are a sort of foretaste of heaven.

06:54.762 --> 07:01.351
Heaven is an eternity of searching out the deep and mysterious and holy things of God.

07:01.752 --> 07:03.474
We'll leave behind

07:03.746 --> 07:07.051
all these particular things that preoccupy us in this life.

07:07.672 --> 07:10.456
Why would I ever say, well, those are the important things.

07:10.537 --> 07:11.178
They're not.

07:11.799 --> 07:15.925
They're not, relatively speaking, they're very unimportant things.

07:15.945 --> 07:21.894
Knowledge and understanding, order me, orient me toward what really matters.

07:22.756 --> 07:24.158
They're a gift of the Holy Spirit.

07:25.901 --> 07:28.685
Next, we have the gift of counsel.

07:29.987 --> 07:31.890
Counsel, what's that?

07:32.514 --> 07:33.595
It's a practical gift.

07:33.955 --> 07:39.521
So if wisdom is a contemplative attitude, I'm going to see the world from the standpoint of God.

07:40.382 --> 07:44.566
Knowledge, understanding, I'm going to search out the meaning of divine truths.

07:44.726 --> 07:46.568
Okay, those are more speculative.

07:47.669 --> 07:49.531
Council, it's practical.

07:50.892 --> 07:54.696
Thomas Aquas refers to what he calls recto-rotzio-agebillium.

07:55.217 --> 07:58.200
That means with typical scholastic understatement.

07:59.101 --> 08:00.562
Right reason

08:00.898 --> 08:02.840
in regard to things to be done.

08:04.882 --> 08:07.284
How do you know what's the right thing to do?

08:07.344 --> 08:18.415
Well, look, in different areas of life, let's see you're a carpenter, let's say you're an economist, you're a financier, you've got a feel for the right thing to do in those areas, the right move to make.

08:19.816 --> 08:26.662
But what's the right move to make when it comes to our relationship to God?

08:28.184 --> 08:30.386
The deepest, most important relationship we have,

08:31.874 --> 08:34.217
What's the morally right thing to do?

08:35.619 --> 08:38.363
What would God want me to do in this situation?

08:39.565 --> 08:43.690
Council is a kind of practical feel for that.

08:44.872 --> 08:48.557
You know, I'm a very bad golfer, like almost all amateurs, right?

08:48.577 --> 08:54.245
I'm kind of happy when I take a swipe at the ball and it kind of advances down the course.

08:54.265 --> 08:56.047
Yeah, I'm pretty happy with that.

08:56.067 --> 09:01.074
But think of a pro golfer and they talk about course management.

09:01.186 --> 09:04.690
The great golfers are thinking their way through a course.

09:04.710 --> 09:07.513
They know exactly how far they can hit their driver.

09:07.553 --> 09:12.078
They know for the second shots, best on this hole to be positioned on the right side of the fairway.

09:12.098 --> 09:13.620
And you've got to get over that bunker.

09:13.640 --> 09:15.682
If you're in front of that bunker, you're not going to make it in two.

09:16.303 --> 09:19.827
And then approaching that green, well, it's got a slope from left to right.

09:19.867 --> 09:24.672
So I don't want to get on the wrong side of that slope, or there's trouble to the right.

09:24.692 --> 09:26.514
So the miss is to the left.

09:27.202 --> 09:30.267
Again, I'm just kind of hitting the ball hoping it gets off the ground.

09:30.708 --> 09:36.919
But a real golfer is exercising a sort of form of practical reason.

09:38.181 --> 09:40.845
Now apply that to the moral order.

09:40.906 --> 09:46.435
If we think golf is complicated, which it is, and having a kind of skill at that is something admirable.

09:47.096 --> 09:52.786
How much more to have a skill in regard to what matters the most?

09:54.562 --> 09:58.087
My relationship to God, living according to God's plans.

09:58.488 --> 10:06.040
Think here of the little flowers little way, right, to find the path of love in the present moment.

10:06.060 --> 10:12.129
Well, that's someone who has counsel that has a feel for what the most loving thing to do would be.

10:12.169 --> 10:14.373
That's a gift of the Holy Spirit.

10:15.394 --> 10:17.037
Next one, fortitude.

10:18.739 --> 10:20.562
Look in every superhero story.

10:22.082 --> 10:25.166
Every superhero requires courage or fortitude.

10:26.268 --> 10:26.508
Why?

10:27.229 --> 10:33.717
Because it'll be otherwise in the next world, but in this world to do the right thing will always be difficult.

10:34.298 --> 10:36.141
And I say that the older I get, the more I believe it.

10:36.161 --> 10:46.194
I say that without fear of contradiction, to do the right thing in this fallen world, this fallen conflictual world will always cost

10:46.818 --> 10:49.160
It'll always involve something like struggle.

10:49.521 --> 10:57.088
Someone's going to stand to thwart you, trust me, and the more you walk the path of the Lord, the more you should expect that opposition.

10:58.008 --> 11:05.515
And therefore, everyone that tries to live according to God's will needs the gift of courage, of fortitude.

11:06.336 --> 11:11.361
I tell the confirmation kids that all the time, Konfirmare in Latin means to strengthen.

11:12.202 --> 11:14.704
It's a strengthening sacrament and fortitude.

11:15.325 --> 11:16.786
That's the courage we need.

11:17.090 --> 11:19.232
to walk the path of the Lord.

11:20.654 --> 11:21.735
Next one is piety.

11:22.796 --> 11:27.741
This one I think is most often written off because pious has a bad sort of overtone in English.

11:28.943 --> 11:30.244
That person is very pious.

11:31.465 --> 11:38.593
It seems to indicate a kind of fussy, superficial religiosity like the Dana Carvey's church lady is pious.

11:38.953 --> 11:40.114
Who wants to be called pious?

11:40.635 --> 11:43.538
But pious is a very strong word actually in our tradition.

11:44.002 --> 11:46.125
Think of Aeneas and the great Aeneid.

11:46.705 --> 11:49.028
His adjective is Pius, is Pius.

11:49.669 --> 11:50.430
That wasn't mean here.

11:50.790 --> 11:57.599
It means something like a keen sense of what is owed to God.

11:57.639 --> 12:02.565
Thomas Aquinas says that religion is a virtue of justice.

12:03.226 --> 12:03.446
Why?

12:03.486 --> 12:09.394
Because religion is giving to God, namely worship and praise, what is owed to him?

12:09.954 --> 12:12.818
See, justice is rendering to each his due.

12:12.930 --> 12:14.191
That's the classical definition.

12:14.532 --> 12:20.798
But what's due to God, who created us, who sustains us in being, what's due to God is praise.

12:21.799 --> 12:31.709
That's why the fact that, what, 75% of my fellow religious, fellow Catholics aren't going to mass on a regular basis, that's a failure of piety.

12:33.171 --> 12:36.294
That's a failure of religion, which means a failure of justice.

12:36.975 --> 12:40.018
The pious person knows what is owed to God.

12:40.514 --> 12:44.418
and enters with enthusiasm into the act of worship.

12:45.859 --> 12:49.022
The last one is my favorite, actually.

12:49.323 --> 12:50.984
It's called the fear of the Lord.

12:52.045 --> 12:55.008
Timor Gomini, the fear of the Lord.

12:55.088 --> 12:57.931
And again, it doesn't mean you're afraid of God.

12:59.453 --> 12:59.993
What does it mean?

13:00.294 --> 13:00.954
I'll put it this way.

13:02.075 --> 13:08.722
Fear of the Lord means, I'm more afraid of not doing God's will.

13:09.954 --> 13:12.317
than I am of any danger in the world.

13:14.439 --> 13:17.904
So doing the will of God, that means you're not gonna be popular.

13:18.765 --> 13:19.225
Oh, I don't care.

13:19.506 --> 13:21.328
I'm more afraid I'm not doing God's will.

13:22.229 --> 13:25.113
Doing God's will means they're all gonna hate you.

13:25.173 --> 13:26.354
You're gonna lose your job.

13:26.394 --> 13:28.457
You're gonna lose your reputation.

13:28.517 --> 13:30.479
Yeah, I know.

13:31.260 --> 13:36.066
But I'm more afraid of not doing God's will or pushing out of the extreme.

13:36.647 --> 13:39.410
Doing God's will means they're gonna kill you.

13:40.578 --> 13:44.282
Look at every martyr in our tradition, extraordinary number of martyrs.

13:44.362 --> 13:50.029
In fact, 20th century had more martyrs than all the previous centuries combined.

13:50.649 --> 13:53.112
Martyrdom is part of Catholic and Christian life.

13:54.273 --> 13:55.355
What does a martyr say?

13:55.415 --> 14:02.162
I'm more afraid of not doing God's will than I am of being killed.

14:03.864 --> 14:04.845
You know what that is, everybody?

14:04.885 --> 14:06.607
That's called fear of the Lord.

14:07.468 --> 14:09.170
That's fear of the Lord.

14:09.282 --> 14:10.604
gift of the Holy Spirit.

14:12.126 --> 14:18.416
Okay, Isaiah chapter 11, take a look, get out or Google it, look up the gifts of the Holy Spirit.

14:19.458 --> 14:21.240
They come with the Messiah.

14:21.280 --> 14:23.063
They come with Him.

14:23.664 --> 14:28.592
And so as we await the arrival of the Messiah Christmas, we're longing for these gifts.

14:30.114 --> 14:36.343
The best thing we can do, watch for them, wait for them, pray for them.

14:37.465 --> 14:38.066
And God bless you.

14:42.978 --> 14:46.572
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

14:46.994 --> 14:52.114
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

